-- Gold Rises to One-Week High; Silver Climbs: Commodities at Close
-- B y   T h o m a s   G a l a t o l a
-- 2013-04-22T20:57:49Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-22/gold-rises-to-one-week-high-silver-climbs-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI Spot
Index of 24  raw materials  rose 0.3 percent to settle at 609.1 at
3:54 p.m.  New York  time, led by gold.  The UBS Bloomberg CMCI  gauge  of 26 prices declined 0.1
percent to 1,457.72.  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold climbed to a one-week high on demand for bars and
coins following the biggest price slump in three decades, while
 Japan  plans to push ahead on stimulus measures.  The volume for the Shanghai Gold Exchange’s benchmark cash
contract today exceeded 43,000 kilograms (43 metric tons) for
the first time. The  U.S. Mint  has sold 167,500 ounces of gold
coins in April, compared with 62,000 ounces in all of March.
 Bank of Japan  Governor Haruhiko Kuroda said he would go ahead
with the campaign to defeat deflation after the G-20 offered no
opposition to the monetary stimulus policies.  On the Comex in New York, gold futures for June delivery
rose 1.8 percent to $1,421.20 an ounce after reaching $1,438.80,
the highest for a most-active contract since April 15.  Silver futures for July delivery advanced 1.6 percent to
$23.374 an ounce, snapping a three-session slump.  On the  New York Mercantile Exchange , platinum futures for
July delivery climbed 0.9 percent to $1,436.80 an ounce.  Palladium futures for June delivery rose 0.7 percent to
$681.90 an ounce, the third straight session.  CRUDE OIL  Crude oil advanced to a one-week high as the Group of 20
nations approved of Japan’s stimulus program, bolstering
speculation that fuel demand will climb in the third-biggest
oil-consuming nation.  On the Nymex, oil futures for May delivery climbed 0.9
percent to $88.76 a barrel.  Brent oil for June settlement rose 0.7 percent to $100.39 a
barrel on the London-based ICE Futures Europe exchange.  Gunvor Group Ltd. sold a cargo of North Sea Forties crude
at a lower differential than the previous trade, while Total SA
failed to buy the grade for the second straight session.  Iraq plans to cut exports of its Kirkuk crude in May from
the Turkish port of Ceyhan to 15 cargoes, four less than this
month, a loading program obtained by  Bloomberg News  showed.  OIL PRODUCTS  Ultra low-sulfur diesel rose for the third straight session
as crude oil climbed.  On the Nymex, ultra low-sulfur diesel for May delivery
advanced 0.8 percent to $2.8094 a gallon.  Gasoline futures for May delivery fell 0.1 percent to
$2.7694 a gallon.  NATURAL GAS  Natural gas fell the most in nine weeks as forecasts showed
moderating temperatures that would limit heating demand.  On the Nymex, gas futures for May delivery tumbled 3.2
percent to $4.267 per million British thermal units, the biggest
drop since Feb. 14.  U.K. gas dropped as much as 3.3 percent to 64.8 pence a
therm, the lowest since Jan. 31, according to broker prices
compiled by Bloomberg. A therm is 100,000 Btu.  GRAINS, OILSEEDS  Corn dropped to the lowest in more than a week on
speculation that planting will accelerate in the U.S., the
world’s biggest exporter.  On the Chicago Board of Trade, corn futures for July
delivery slumped 1.5 percent to $6.235 a bushel. Earlier, the
price touched $6.1825, the lowest since April 10.  Soybean futures for July delivery dropped 1.3 percent to
$13.6425 a bushel, the biggest decline in a week.  Wheat futures for delivery in July fell 1.3 percent to
$7.025 a bushel.  SOFT COMMODITIES  Sugar fell on speculation that sales by producers will cap
rallies amid signs of lower import demand from  China .  On ICE Futures U.S. in New York, raw sugar for July
delivery declined 0.8 percent to 17.74 cents a pound.  Orange-juice futures for July delivery slumped 2.5 percent
to $1.4325 a pound, the biggest drop since March 20.  Cocoa futures for delivery for July slid 1 percent to
$2,310 a metric ton.  Arabica-coffee futures for July delivery fell 0.1 percent
to $1.431 a pound.  Cotton futures for July delivery gained 0.9 percent to
86.15 cents a pound.  BASE METALS  Copper dropped for the second straight session as lower
imports by China and an unexpected drop in U.S. home sales
fueled concern that metal demand is weakening.  On the Comex, copper futures for July delivery fell 0.6
percent to $3.144 a pound.  On the London Metal Exchange, copper for delivery in three
months slid 0.8 percent to $6,935 a ton ($3.15 a pound). Zinc
and lead declined, while aluminum, tin and nickel rose.  LIVESTOCK  Cattle futures fell on signs of increasing supplies of
animals in the U.S.  On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, cattle futures for June
delivery declined 0.4 percent to $1.20825 a pound. The price
declined for the third straight session, the longest slide since
March 15.  Feeder-cattle futures for August settlement fell 0.1
percent to $1.45975 a pound.  Hog futures for June settlement slipped 0.8 percent to
89.45 cents a pound on the CME.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Thomas Galatola in New York at 
